# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1969-70-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] The **1969–70 Vehicle & General Australasian knock-out competition** was a List A tournament took place from November 1969 to January 1970.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1969-70-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] It was the first season of the Australian domestic limited-overs cricket tournament.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1969-70-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] Seven teams representing the six states in Australia, and a New Zealand team, took part in the competition in a knockout format.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1969-70-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] The competition began on 22 November 1969 when Victoria took on Tasmania at the Melbourne Cricket Ground.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1969-70-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] After five matches were played, the final took place on 1 January 1970 at the Melbourne Cricket Ground between Victoria and New Zealand.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1969-70-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] After winning the toss, Victoria were bowled out for 129, with New Zealand chasing the total down with six wickets to spare.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1969-70-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] The first season of the competition was a straight knockout competition between the six states of Australia and a team that represented New Zealand at domestic level.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1970-71-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] The **1970–71 Vehicle & General Australasian knock-out competition** was the second edition of the official List A domestic tournament in Australia.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1970-71-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] Seven teams representing six states in Australia and New Zealand took part in the knock-out competition.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1970-71-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] The competition began on 18 October 1970 when South Australia took on Victoria at the Adelaide Oval.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1970-71-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] The 1970–71 cup final was played on 6 February 1971 at the Melbourne Cricket Ground between Queensland and Western Australia, with Western Australia recording an 91 run victory over Queensland.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1970-71-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] Ian Chappell scored the most runs in the tournament with 176 runs with Graham McKenzie from Western Australia taking the most wickets with eight.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1970-71-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] The second season of the competition was a straight knockout competition between the six states of Australia and a team that represented New Zealand at the domestic level.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1979-80-australia-tri-nation-series] The **Benson & Hedges World Series Cup** was a cricket tournament held in Australia from 27 November 1979 to 22 January 1980.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1979-80-australia-tri-nation-series] It was a tri-nations series featuring Australia, England and the West Indies, with all of the matches being played as One Day Internationals (ODI).
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1979-80-australia-tri-nation-series] The series was part of the English and West Indian tour and was the first official tri-nations series after World Series Cricket.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1979-80-australia-tri-nation-series] After the round-robin matches which were played at four venues in Adelaide, Brisbane, Melbourne and Sydney.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1979-80-australia-tri-nation-series] England and the West Indies reached the final where the West Indies won the final series 2–0.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1979-80-australia-tri-nation-series] The red ball was used and the white pads were worn for the matches in Adelaide, Brisbane and Melbourne, and the white ball was used and the coloured pads were worn for the matches in Sydney.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1979-80-australia-tri-nation-series] England and West Indies would not contest the tri-series again until the 1986-87 season.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1980-81-australia-tri-nation-series] The **1980–81 Australia Tri-Nation Series** (more commonly known as the **1980–81 World Series**) was a cricket tournament held in Australia from 23 November 1980 to 3 February 1981.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1980-81-australia-tri-nation-series] It was the second edition of the Australian Tri-Series, with Australia playing host to India and New Zealand.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1980-81-australia-tri-nation-series] The series was a part of the Indian and New Zealand tours.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1980-81-australia-tri-nation-series] After matches were played in Adelaide, Brisbane, Melbourne, Sydney and Perth throughout the entire group-stage, Australia and New Zealand qualified for the finals where after the underarm incident in the third final, Australia went on to win 3–1.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1981-82-australia-tri-nation-series] The **1981–82 World Series** was a One Day International (ODI) cricket tri-series where Australia played host to Pakistan and West Indies.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1981-82-australia-tri-nation-series] Australia and West Indies reached the Finals, with West Indies winning the best-of-five final series 3–1.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1981-82-australia-tri-nation-series] West Indies won the best of five final series against Australia 3–1.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1982-83-australian-tri-series] The **1982–83 Benson & Hedges World Series Cup** was a One Day International (ODI) cricket tri-series where Australia played host to England and New Zealand.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1982-83-australian-tri-series] Australia and New Zealand reached the Finals, which Australia won 2–0.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1982-83-australian-tri-series] Australia won the best of three final series against New Zealand 2–0.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1983-84-australian-tri-series] The **1983–84 World Series** was a One Day International (ODI) cricket tri-series where Australia played host to Pakistan and West Indies.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1983-84-australian-tri-series] Australia and West Indies reached the Finals, which West Indies won 2–0.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1983-84-australian-tri-series] West Indies won the best of three final series against Australia 2–0.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] The **1993–94 Australia Tri-Nation Series** (more commonly known as the **1993–94 World Series**) was a One Day International (ODI) tri-series cricket tournament in Australia.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] The host nation's cricket team played matches against New Zealand and South Africa at six venues across Australia.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] The tournament featured a quadruple round-robin tournament, with the matches being split into two groups of six matches each, and two test matches in the South African series being played at the halfway point.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] After twelve matches were played, Australia finished on top and took on South Africa, which finished just ahead of New Zealand by net run rate after they were both tied at seven points apiece.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] In the final series, after losing the first match at the Melbourne Cricket Ground, Australia went on to win the remaining two matches played at the Sydney Cricket Ground, winning 2-1 and recording their eighth title.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] Mark Waugh, from Australia, finished as the leading run scorer of the tournament, with 391 runs, while teammate Shane Warne was the leading wicket-taker, with 20 wickets.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] The series began in Melbourne under a warning, after the debacle of the warm-up match between Victoria and South Africa, which saw the run-ups being covered by rubber mats.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] The South Africans won the opening match of the tournament by seven wickets, with a 140-run partnership between Kepler Wessels (70) and Hansie Cronje (91) securing the victory.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] This was despite Australia bringing in Shane Warne after Tim May was ruled out with a hamstring muscle strain.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] After the match at Adelaide Oval between New Zealand and South Africa was washed out without a ball being played, Australia recorded their first victory of the series as they defeated New Zealand by eight wickets.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] This was due to part to Glenn McGrath and Warne each taking four wickets as they bowled New Zealand out for only 135, and in part to Matthew Hayden scoring a half-century in what was first ODI in Australia.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] When the tournament moved to Sydney, Australia recorded their second victory in a row with a rout of South Africa on a pitch that Captain Allan Border called "shocking".
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] This was after South Africa was bowled for 69, with Paul Reiffel taking four wickets for 13 runs in his eight overs to lose by 103 runs.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] Australia went on to win the match played at Melbourne, with the host team winning by 3 runs over New Zealand on the back of an 81-run innings from Mark Taylor, as Steve Waugh tore a hamstring and was ruled out for the first two tests against South Africa.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] In Hobart, South Africa could only muster 7/147 from their fifty overs on what *The Age* described as a 200-run pitch.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] This was helped by good bowling from man-of-the-match Gavin Larsen (2/12) and Chris Pringle (3/28).
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] New Zealand, with Brendan Young the top scorer with 74, chased the target with four wickets to spare.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] After the first two tests of the South African series were played in Melbourne and Sydney, the tournament restarted at the Gabba, in Brisbane, for the second half of the tournament.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] New Zealand, with the partnership of Shane Thomson (68) and Chris Cairns (70), would get to 7/256, which would be the highest score of the tournament.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] They would go on to win by nine runs in a revised target of 227, despite Peter Kirsten (97).
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] South Africa would suffer another defeat, this time to Australia only one day later, as 98 runs in 158 minutes from Dean Jones led Australia to a 48-run win.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] The following match, played at the Sydney Cricket Ground, saw a controversial not-out call when umpire Steve Davis rejected a straight forward catch from Ken Rutherford batting to Shane Warne.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] Allan Border stated that it was an out and called for the umpires to use common sense.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] This call would later be costly, with Rutherford scoring 65 and, with the help of Chris Pringle who took four wickets, leading New Zealand to a 13-run win over Australia.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] Two matches were then played at Perth's WACA.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] In the first match, three wickets from Brian McMillan and Allan Donald (two being in the first over) helped South Africa record a five-wicket victory with twenty overs left to spare as they chased down the 151 set by New Zealand.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] The second match was another South African victory, this time over a weakened Australia, which didn't have Ian Healy as wicket keeper, as he had been replaced by Tim Zoehrer.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] Other health issues included Peter Kirsten being hit on the side of the face, with X-ray scans showing two fractures of his cheek bone.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] The final match of the group stage saw an 121-run partnership between Boon and Dean Jones, as they led Australia to 3/217 on a slow outfield.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] In response, New Zealand could muster only 166, with Bryan Young the top scorer with 45, as Warne took three wickets.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] This meant that South Africa qualified through to the finals by net run rate.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] The final series of matches started at the Melbourne Cricket Ground, with Craig McDermott being brought back into the lineup for Australia, while Peter Kirsten was put in the lineup for South Africa despite the facial bone fractures he received in the previous match.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] In the opening match, a century from Gary Kirsten and a five-wicket haul from Richard Snell guided the visitors to a 28-run victory, as they opened up a 1–0 series lead heading into the Sydney matches.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] The first match of two at the Sydney Cricket Ground saw a partnership of 175 between Mark Waugh (107) and Jones (79) as they led Australia to 6/247 from their fifty overs.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] "Purple patch" performances from bowlers Warne (3/4 from 15 balls) and McDermott (3/6 from eight balls) would help in bowling out South Africa for 178, 69 runs short of the target.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] This was despite a half century from Jonty Rhodes.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] The final match saw Australia win by 35 runs in Border's 100th match as captain in the tri-series.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] Half centuries from Mark Waugh (who was named player of the final series) and Boon got Australia to 223, which South Africa wouldn't reach as they only scored 9/188.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] Mark Waugh finished the tournament with the most runs in the series, 524, which included a century in the second final against South Africa.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] He finished ahead of fellow Australian batsmen David Boon and Dean Jones.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] South African players Gary Kirsten and Hansie Cronje rounded out the top five.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] Shane Warne ended the series as the leading wicket taker, with 20 wickets from ten matches.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] He was followed by fellow Australian Glenn McGrath, who ended up with the same number of wickets as Kiwi bowler Chris Pringle.
[src:1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series/1993-94-australia-tri-nation-series] South African Fanie de Villiers and Australian Paul Reiffel rounded out the top five.
